The '''Native American Literature Symposium''' ('''NALS''') is a leading [[Native American studies]] conference.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hoop.aisc.ucla.edu/nalitsymp.htm |title=Project HOOP: Native American Literature |work=hoop.aisc.ucla.edu |publisher=UCLA American Indian Studies Center |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref> It was founded in 2001.<ref name="About NALS">{{cite web |url=http://www.mnsu.edu/nativelit/aboutnals.html |title=About NALS |work=MNSU.edu |publisher=The Native American Literature Symposium |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref> It is held at a tribal venue every spring.<ref>{{cite book |first=Penelope Myrtle |last=Kelsey |title=Tribal Theory in Native American Literature: Dakota and Haudenosaunee Writing and Indigenous Worldviews |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |year=2008 |page=132 |isbn=9780803227712}}</ref> The NALS was first established by a group of independent scholars committed to creating a place where Native voices can be heard.<ref name="About NALS" /> The current Director is [[Gwen N. Westerman]] of [[Minnesota State University, Mankato]].<ref name="About NALS"/>
