The '''Uzawa–Lucas model''' is an [[economic model]] of [[Endogenous growth theory|endogenous growth]] developed by [[Robert Lucas, Jr.]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lucas, Robert |title=On the Mechanics of Economic Development |journal=[[Journal of Monetary Economics]] |year=1988 |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=3–42 |doi=10.1016/0304-3932(88)90168-7}}</ref> building upon initial contributions by [[Hirofumi Uzawa]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Hirofumi |last=Uzawa |title=Optimum Technical Change in An Aggregative Model of Economic Growth |journal=[[International Economic Review]] |volume=6 |issue=1 |year=1965 |pages=18–31 |jstor=2525621 }}</ref> It extends the [[AK model]] by a two-sector setup, in which physical and [[human capital]] are produced by different technologies. The model explains long-run economic growth as consequence of human capital accumulation.

== Background ==
Lucas approaches in a series of papers published in the 1970s were a challenge to the classic principles of [[Keynesian economics]] when he suggested an amassed version of microeconomics models and then emphasized on human capital accumulation. In his 1988 dissection, using [[Ramsey–Cass–Koopmans model|Ramsey framework]] and [[Cobb–Douglas production function|Cobb-Douglas production function]] Lucas gave more attention to formal education rather than [[learning-by-doing]]. While in [[Solow–Swan model|Solow-Swan model]] human capital is constant which leads to no transitional dynamics, Lucas measures total capital as the ratio of physical to human capital, not as sum<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maplesoft.com/applications/view.aspx?sid=7170&view=html|title=I like this Maple Application - The Uzawa Lucas Growth Model|website=www.maplesoft.com|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>. 

In the original paper, Lucas described the properties of both centralized and decentralized economics evolving with balanced paths. 

